1
00:03:09,523 --> 00:03:12,984
I say there'll be a crowd at the house
tonight for you, Jimmy, huh?

2
00:03:13,068 --> 00:03:15,319
When did they let you out, Mossie?

3
00:03:15,404 --> 00:03:19,740
Just a month ago,
after the new government came in, like.

4
00:03:20,826 --> 00:03:22,159
How long did you serve?

5
00:03:22,995 --> 00:03:24,579
3 years.

6
00:03:26,206 --> 00:03:28,165
Awful tough on Angela.

7
00:03:29,668 --> 00:03:32,879
We had to send our eldest one, Kate,
off to her auntie in Scotland.

8
00:03:34,214 --> 00:03:38,593
- Is she back yet?
- Nah, I have to find some work first.

9
00:04:34,858 --> 00:04:37,026
Sorry old state now, Jimmy, huh?

10
00:04:38,320 --> 00:04:42,031
Meself and Tommy keep an eye on the roof
as best we can like, but...

11
00:04:43,408 --> 00:04:44,951
Some ghosts in there, eh?

12
00:04:45,994 --> 00:04:47,370
I still miss it.

13
00:04:48,997 --> 00:04:50,122
Go on, Dixie.

14
00:04:57,798 --> 00:05:00,549
Go on, Dixie. Walk on.

15
00:05:04,179 --> 00:05:05,346
Well, now.

16
00:05:08,892 --> 00:05:11,310
Whoa, Dixie. Stand there now.

17
00:05:17,025 --> 00:05:18,484
Stand.

18
00:05:18,568 --> 00:05:20,111
Mam!

19
00:05:20,195 --> 00:05:21,404
James!

20
00:05:31,289 --> 00:05:34,250
- You're back.
- How are you?

21
00:05:34,334 --> 00:05:36,377
Too long. Too long.

22
00:05:36,461 --> 00:05:39,588
I know. Sorry I didn't make it back
for Charlie's funeral.

23
00:05:39,673 --> 00:05:42,216
Just been to the grave.

24
00:05:42,300 --> 00:05:46,470
Oh, he was a good son,
but this farm is a mess without him.

25
00:05:52,769 --> 00:05:55,312
Ah, you bastard.

26
00:06:22,799 --> 00:06:23,966
God bless you, Jimmy.

27
00:06:33,060 --> 00:06:35,770
Hey-hey!

28
00:06:35,854 --> 00:06:38,064
Where's this bloody rogue?

29
00:06:38,148 --> 00:06:40,524
I could smell you were back.

30
00:06:40,609 --> 00:06:43,069
Great to see you.
I can't believe they let you out.

31
00:06:43,153 --> 00:06:45,696
About bloody time. Did you get lost?

32
00:06:45,781 --> 00:06:48,824
You were sorely missed, Jimmy.
Great to have you back.

33
00:06:48,909 --> 00:06:49,950
Thank you, Finn.

34
00:06:50,035 --> 00:06:52,244
- I believe you got married recently.
- I did.

35
00:06:52,329 --> 00:06:54,955
There's some fierce desperate women
in Leitrim...

36
00:06:56,541 --> 00:06:59,418
Well, Jimmy. Jimmy.

37
00:06:59,503 --> 00:07:02,213
You must have been around the world
20 times by now.

38
00:07:02,297 --> 00:07:05,091
Well, thanks be to God
you're back here now with your mother

39
00:07:05,175 --> 00:07:07,510
because, you know,
it was lonely here for her.

40
00:07:07,594 --> 00:07:09,011
Very, very lonely.

41
00:07:09,096 --> 00:07:11,347
I missed you so much.

42
00:07:11,431 --> 00:07:15,434
Well, I'm home now to look
after you. It's great to see you all.

43
00:07:15,519 --> 00:07:17,061
Lovely to see you, Jimmy.

44
00:07:17,145 --> 00:07:19,230
What will you do
with yourself, Jimmy?

45
00:07:19,314 --> 00:07:23,859
Well, I'll settle back down with Mam,
and I've missed the land.

46
00:07:23,944 --> 00:07:26,946
- I want a quiet life now.
- Oh, I'll take bets on that.

47
00:07:27,030 --> 00:07:29,073
Eh? A quiet life.

48
00:07:29,157 --> 00:07:30,574
You're on! 10 to 1.

49
00:07:30,659 --> 00:07:33,410
I'll have some of your Yankee dollars
off you, boy, huh?

50
00:07:33,495 --> 00:07:35,079
I'm gonna hold you to that.

51
00:07:47,634 --> 00:07:50,719
Oonagh. Oonagh!

52
00:07:58,395 --> 00:08:01,647
- For your children.
- Oh, thank you.

53
00:08:06,987 --> 00:08:08,737
For you.

54
00:08:10,782 --> 00:08:12,032
OK.

55
00:08:16,830 --> 00:08:18,247
You look well, Oonagh.

56
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:23,169
A bit grey around the edges.

57
00:08:23,253 --> 00:08:25,546
Still like a hungry whippet, though.

58
00:08:28,216 --> 00:08:30,426
Why did you stop writing, Jimmy?

59
00:08:31,553 --> 00:08:32,970
You know why.

60
00:08:36,433 --> 00:08:37,850
How are the children?

61
00:08:38,768 --> 00:08:41,562
Healthy. Full of spirit, thank God.

62
00:08:42,981 --> 00:08:47,860
- And Fintan?
- A good, steady man. Loving father.

63
00:08:49,279 --> 00:08:53,866
- You?
- Ah. Same as ever.

64
00:08:54,993 --> 00:08:57,578
Nobody's the same
after 10 years, Jimmy.

65
00:09:00,081 --> 00:09:03,375
I have to get back. Thanks for these.

66
00:10:24,416 --> 00:10:25,499
Hey, Jimmy.

67
00:10:40,724 --> 00:10:42,516
He's very quiet.

68
00:10:43,727 --> 00:10:45,394
Ah, give him time.

69
00:10:47,188 --> 00:10:49,148
He's not the same man
that went away.

70
00:10:49,232 --> 00:10:51,358
- Ah, he'll settle.
- Will he?

71
00:10:53,486 --> 00:10:55,279
He might. He might.

72
00:10:58,783 --> 00:11:01,327
Far cry from New York,
eh, Jimmy?

73
00:11:01,411 --> 00:11:03,370
You don't get this down on Broadway.

74
00:11:04,706 --> 00:11:09,001
And here you are back down
the same feckin' bog in Leitrim, huh?

75
00:11:09,085 --> 00:11:11,545
- Wet feet.
- And a wet arse.

76
00:11:15,216 --> 00:11:19,970
Aye, but nobody yelling orders at ya.
Can't beat that.

77
00:11:25,101 --> 00:11:27,936
Well, word... word travels fast.

78
00:11:30,732 --> 00:11:32,941
Must be a great relief
to see your son again.

79
00:11:33,026 --> 00:11:34,151
It is.

80
00:11:35,153 --> 00:11:38,447
- Is he well?
- He's very well, Father.

81
00:11:38,531 --> 00:11:39,948
Thank you.

82
00:11:41,201 --> 00:11:43,869
A lot of water under the bridge.

83
00:11:43,953 --> 00:11:45,996
But, you know,
New York is a tough place.

84
00:11:46,081 --> 00:11:50,751
It'll be quite a shock from city life
to our humble country ways.

85
00:11:52,587 --> 00:11:55,422
Do you think he's matured?

86
00:11:55,507 --> 00:11:59,468
Well, we all change, Father.
Wouldn't you agree?

87
00:11:59,552 --> 00:12:03,097
Well, God willing,
we all change for the better.

88
00:12:03,181 --> 00:12:06,892
Do you think he'll, er...
do you think he'll stay?

89
00:12:06,976 --> 00:12:09,812
He was born in this house, Father.

90
00:12:10,855 --> 00:12:13,774
The decision will be his.
I will leave that up to him.

91
00:12:13,858 --> 00:12:17,444
You know, we've suffered great violence
in this country, Alice.

92
00:12:17,529 --> 00:12:18,570
Yeah.

93
00:12:18,655 --> 00:12:21,782
Brother against brother,
and neighbour against neighbour.

94
00:12:22,867 --> 00:12:25,786
Scars on the heart,
they take a long time to heal.

95
00:12:26,996 --> 00:12:32,251
But I... I sense a new atmosphere,
you know, of... of change.

96
00:12:32,335 --> 00:12:34,002
Of forgiveness.

97
00:12:35,505 --> 00:12:37,089
Would you agree?

98
00:12:38,007 --> 00:12:41,885
Oh, I would agree, Father,
but there must be mutual respect.

99
00:12:41,970 --> 00:12:45,639
Well, let's pray there'll be
no slipping back to the old ways.

100
00:12:46,724 --> 00:12:48,183
Oh, by the way, tell your son

101
00:12:48,268 --> 00:12:51,728
if the quietness of the country
gets too much for a man of action,

102
00:12:51,813 --> 00:12:55,899
I have some excellent contacts in London
who could find him a very good job,

103
00:12:55,984 --> 00:13:01,280
which, of course, would be a great
relief to a mother in these hard times.

104
00:13:03,450 --> 00:13:06,285
Where would you be now
without a nice cup of tea, huh?

105
00:13:06,369 --> 00:13:09,997
Absolutely lost, Father.

106
00:14:09,807 --> 00:14:11,975
- Come on. Come on.
- Come on, boy.

107
00:14:13,853 --> 00:14:15,687
Sorry to stop your fun.

108
00:14:19,943 --> 00:14:22,069
Are you who I think you are?

109
00:14:22,153 --> 00:14:23,862
Are you, J... Jimmy Gralton?

110
00:14:23,947 --> 00:14:25,697
And who wants to know?

111
00:14:25,782 --> 00:14:27,533
My name's Marie O'Keefe.

112
00:14:27,951 --> 00:14:29,493
Daughter of Dennis O'Keefe?

113
00:14:29,577 --> 00:14:31,870
He hates you with a passion.

114
00:14:31,955 --> 00:14:34,498
Nearly had a fit
when the priest said you were back.

115
00:14:34,582 --> 00:14:36,458
Did he now? Come on.

116
00:14:43,967 --> 00:14:46,718
Dance away now.

117
00:14:48,638 --> 00:14:50,264
Have you seen O'Keefe?

118
00:14:50,348 --> 00:14:55,352
He left the Free State Army a few years
back there after his first wife died.

119
00:14:55,436 --> 00:14:57,271
He was on his own
with Marie for a while,

120
00:14:57,355 --> 00:14:59,731
and then he struck gold
and married into land.

121
00:14:59,816 --> 00:15:02,067
He's mad as hell
about the change of government,

122
00:15:02,151 --> 00:15:03,902
calling de Valera a communist.

123
00:15:03,987 --> 00:15:08,073
Big shot now in the Army Comrades
Association. You know them?

124
00:15:08,157 --> 00:15:10,826
Yeah, afraid they won't be able
to export to England.

125
00:15:10,910 --> 00:15:12,286
Ah, bunch of fascists.

126
00:15:12,370 --> 00:15:16,081
Stay well clear of him. Nasty as ever.

127
00:15:16,165 --> 00:15:18,292
And with a long memory.

128
00:15:21,129 --> 00:15:23,130
- Jimmy!
- Jimmy!

129
00:15:23,214 --> 00:15:26,008
- Jimmy.
- Whoa, whoa, whoa.

130
00:15:26,092 --> 00:15:29,094
- Stop, stop, stop.
- What's all this, the Wild West?

131
00:15:29,178 --> 00:15:30,846
Can we have a word?

132
00:15:30,930 --> 00:15:33,515
- Well, are we under arrest?
- Not yet, anyway.

133
00:15:33,600 --> 00:15:36,643
- Go ahead, ask him.
- I won't ask him. You ask him.

134
00:15:36,728 --> 00:15:40,188
The hall, Jimmy.
We've all heard stories, lots of them.

135
00:15:40,273 --> 00:15:43,859
My brother's been telling me the stories
of when he used to box in the gym.

136
00:15:43,943 --> 00:15:47,237
Tommy, if the hall was fixed up,
you could do the woodwork lessons.

137
00:15:47,322 --> 00:15:51,325
My uncle did the woodwork lessons. He's
one of the best carpenters in the town.

138
00:15:51,409 --> 00:15:53,785
Tess could use the hall
for her art classes.

139
00:15:53,870 --> 00:15:55,912
The paintings and drawings
are wonderful.

140
00:15:55,997 --> 00:15:57,331
I met Sean yesterday,

141
00:15:57,415 --> 00:16:00,751
and he still has all his poetry
and books from the foreign countries.

142
00:16:00,835 --> 00:16:03,795
He said he'd do the lessons again
if there was a hall there.

143
00:16:03,880 --> 00:16:05,839
He really wants to do it. Please, Jimmy.

144
00:16:05,923 --> 00:16:09,259
And the music by Molly
and the singing by Oonagh.

145
00:16:09,344 --> 00:16:11,428
There's nothing
round here for us.

146
00:16:11,512 --> 00:16:13,889
There's no work.
There's nowhere for us to go.

147
00:16:13,973 --> 00:16:15,891
We can't go to America
the same as yourself.

148
00:16:15,975 --> 00:16:18,644
The rules of immigration has changed.
We're stuck here.

149
00:16:18,728 --> 00:16:22,064
Stop going around in circles.
Just ask the man what we came here for.

150
00:16:22,148 --> 00:16:26,151
We want to dance, Jimmy. Somewhere where
we won't be getting a guard or a priest

151
00:16:26,235 --> 00:16:28,445
poking at us with a stick.

152
00:16:28,529 --> 00:16:32,282
Somewhere warm. Please, Jimmy,
will you open up the hall again?

153
00:16:32,367 --> 00:16:33,575
Aye.

154
00:16:33,660 --> 00:16:36,244
It's falling to pieces.
It's not even safe any more.

155
00:16:38,956 --> 00:16:40,666
You don't understand.

156
00:16:42,710 --> 00:16:45,420
Come on, boy. Come on, boy.
Come on, boy.

157
00:16:47,757 --> 00:16:50,759
Come on, boy. Come on. Come on.

158
00:16:50,843 --> 00:16:53,428
At least think about it, will you?
Think about it, yeah?

159
00:16:53,513 --> 00:16:55,847
So much for the legend
of Jimmy Gralton.

160
00:16:57,558 --> 00:16:59,976
You better change the name of the hall.

161
00:17:00,061 --> 00:17:02,270
James Connolly
will be turning in his grave.

162
00:18:36,449 --> 00:18:38,116
Right. Come on, up.

163
00:18:39,744 --> 00:18:41,870
So, how long have you been
working at this?

164
00:18:41,954 --> 00:18:43,580
Oh, for the past few months,

165
00:18:43,664 --> 00:18:47,417
whenever the lads get a bit of free time,
in the evenings, at the weekends.

166
00:18:47,502 --> 00:18:51,004
We're planning on opening in 2
or 3 weeks, and we're on schedule.

167
00:18:51,088 --> 00:18:53,215
Ah, Dessie, for Jesus' sake!
Hello?

168
00:18:53,341 --> 00:18:55,926
- Can I have one of these?
- Dessie! Come on!

169
00:18:56,010 --> 00:18:59,346
I'm after milking 6 cows this morning.
I'm starved of the hunger.

170
00:18:59,430 --> 00:19:02,015
Jesus, Mary and Joseph,
give me patience!

171
00:19:03,518 --> 00:19:06,186
Look at him with the sandwich
in his mouth.

172
00:19:06,270 --> 00:19:08,730
Up we go. How's that?

173
00:19:08,815 --> 00:19:11,608
- Jesus!
- Shite!

174
00:19:11,692 --> 00:19:13,652
Shite!

175
00:19:15,029 --> 00:19:18,073
The Tans burnt the church hall down
in Gowell about a year ago,

176
00:19:18,157 --> 00:19:21,076
- so we decided to build our own.
- With, er, what money?

177
00:19:21,160 --> 00:19:24,412
I had some savings from the States,
and a few friends, too.

178
00:19:24,497 --> 00:19:27,999
So, if it's your money and your land,
does that mean that it's your hall?

179
00:19:28,084 --> 00:19:31,795
No. It's built by the voluntary labour
of the community,

180
00:19:31,879 --> 00:19:33,755
and it's run by an elected committee.

181
00:19:33,840 --> 00:19:37,175
I'll teach art, and Molly and Oonagh
will teach the music.

182
00:19:37,260 --> 00:19:42,430
And Mossie the boxing,
gymnastics, woodwork. Literature.

183
00:19:42,515 --> 00:19:45,517
And every penny'll go back into the hall
to buy materials.

184
00:19:45,601 --> 00:19:47,394
Musical instruments, books...

185
00:19:47,478 --> 00:19:50,397
And we'll have the best damned dances
in the whole country.

186
00:19:50,481 --> 00:19:54,442
I just spoke to your parish priest.
Not best pleased.

187
00:19:54,527 --> 00:19:57,279
Even said that all the horses
that dragged the sand here

188
00:19:57,405 --> 00:19:59,030
will die within a year.

189
00:19:59,115 --> 00:20:00,866
Is he a priest or a witch doctor?

190
00:20:00,950 --> 00:20:04,452
Our opposition is still the same,
the masters and the pastors.

191
00:21:01,177 --> 00:21:03,595
Come in, Father.
You're welcome.

192
00:21:03,679 --> 00:21:05,555
Gralton, you come out.

193
00:21:05,640 --> 00:21:08,099
It's Mr Gralton to you,
Sheridan.

194
00:21:08,184 --> 00:21:09,935
Who in the hell do you think you are,

195
00:21:10,019 --> 00:21:12,520
running classes in my parish
without my permission?

196
00:21:12,605 --> 00:21:16,316
No permission required.
That's the point, we built it ourselves.

197
00:21:16,400 --> 00:21:20,987
Education is the exclusive reserve
of Holy Mother Church,

198
00:21:21,072 --> 00:21:22,530
not semi-illiterates.

199
00:21:22,615 --> 00:21:25,825
- Don't patronise me.
- No, Jimmy, don't...

200
00:21:25,910 --> 00:21:30,330
I will not have
a communist on my turf defy the Church.

201
00:21:30,414 --> 00:21:32,832
Now, days of tugging the forelock
are gone.

202
00:21:33,793 --> 00:21:36,753
Oh, bare arms.

203
00:21:36,837 --> 00:21:38,380
Hardly becomes you.

204
00:21:38,923 --> 00:21:41,633
Does your father know you're here,
Oonagh Dempsey?

205
00:21:41,717 --> 00:21:45,428
If you'd like to enrol in our dance class,
Father, you're more than welcome.

206
00:21:45,554 --> 00:21:48,515
It doesn't cost a penny,
and we're all volunteers.

207
00:21:55,564 --> 00:21:58,316
I'm here to represent
my neighbour, Rory McManus,

208
00:21:58,401 --> 00:22:00,026
who is the rightful tenant.

209
00:22:00,111 --> 00:22:03,196
That land has been in their family
for over 30 years,

210
00:22:03,280 --> 00:22:06,324
but, due to ill health,
he fell behind on the rent.

211
00:22:06,409 --> 00:22:09,077
That landlord wouldn't give him
the time to catch up,

212
00:22:09,161 --> 00:22:11,246
and he threw him off his land.

213
00:22:11,330 --> 00:22:14,082
My name is Seamus Clarke.
I am the new tenant.

214
00:22:14,166 --> 00:22:17,127
I rented this land in good faith
and for a fair price from the landlord.

215
00:22:17,211 --> 00:22:18,628
Shame on you, Clarke.

216
00:22:18,713 --> 00:22:21,631
You've had your beady eye
on that land next door for years.

217
00:22:21,716 --> 00:22:23,717
Silence in the court.

218
00:22:23,801 --> 00:22:26,386
This court has reached a unanimous decision.

219
00:22:26,470 --> 00:22:31,975
The tenant, Rory McManus, is entitled
to the recovery of the land in dispute.

220
00:22:33,394 --> 00:22:35,937
And the cattle
belonging to Seamus Clarke

221
00:22:36,022 --> 00:22:37,647
will be removed immediately.

222
00:22:43,946 --> 00:22:47,240
Jimmy. Jimmy.

223
00:22:47,366 --> 00:22:49,576
It's O'Keefe.
He's up there with his army.

224
00:22:49,660 --> 00:22:53,246
Doherty's there with his thugs, too.
And the priest is just after arriving.

225
00:22:53,330 --> 00:22:57,167
- You're not gonna get by.
- Good work, son. Good man.

226
00:22:57,251 --> 00:22:58,835
- The Holy Trinity.
- Bastards.

227
00:22:58,919 --> 00:23:01,337
Take it easy.
It's not the Tans we're fighting now.

228
00:23:01,422 --> 00:23:02,464
It's feckin' worse.

229
00:23:03,674 --> 00:23:06,801
Open up, Clarke.
Here's your cattle back.

230
00:23:06,886 --> 00:23:08,928
Keep them off your neighbour's land.

231
00:23:09,013 --> 00:23:11,014
Gralton,
you pay attention to me.

232
00:23:11,098 --> 00:23:14,350
You sow nothing but conflict
in a peaceful community.

233
00:23:14,435 --> 00:23:16,978
Go and join the commies in Siberia.
Leave us alone.

234
00:23:17,063 --> 00:23:18,605
You join the British.

235
00:23:18,689 --> 00:23:21,775
I'll tell you whose land it is.
Where's Rory? Come here, Rory.

236
00:23:21,859 --> 00:23:24,360
McManus, you took advantage
of a tenant in trouble.

237
00:23:24,445 --> 00:23:28,865
This is a statement from
the acting OC of the IRA in this area.

238
00:23:28,949 --> 00:23:31,242
Now, listen up
if you know what's good for you.

239
00:23:31,327 --> 00:23:33,119
We fought the British too, Doherty.

240
00:23:33,204 --> 00:23:35,455
Look at him
having to read for Doherty.

241
00:23:35,539 --> 00:23:37,791
Let him have his word. Read away.

242
00:23:37,875 --> 00:23:41,419
"Whereas certain evilly
disposed and unauthorised persons

243
00:23:41,504 --> 00:23:44,714
"in certain districts
within the area of South Leitrim

244
00:23:44,799 --> 00:23:48,051
"have commandeered and taken
forcible possession of lands

245
00:23:48,135 --> 00:23:50,804
"to which they are not entitled..."

246
00:23:50,888 --> 00:23:55,141
- Yeah, back in 1690.
- Silence, silence, silence!

247
00:23:55,226 --> 00:23:59,145
"We do hereby order
that anyone found commandeering

248
00:23:59,230 --> 00:24:02,690
"or interfering with lands
to which such a person has no claim

249
00:24:02,775 --> 00:24:04,776
"shall be severely dealt with."

250
00:24:04,860 --> 00:24:06,694
Are you threatening us?

251
00:24:06,779 --> 00:24:09,864
We intend to implement
the decision of the Republican court.

252
00:24:09,949 --> 00:24:12,700
- Yes!
- Now stand aside!

253
00:24:12,785 --> 00:24:15,912
Any man goes through that gate
gets a bullet in the head.

254
00:24:15,996 --> 00:24:19,749
- Put those guns away!
- You'll be the first to hit the ground.

255
00:24:19,834 --> 00:24:22,502
Put those guns down immediately!

256
00:24:22,586 --> 00:24:25,255
Put it down! Put them down!

257
00:24:25,339 --> 00:24:28,299
I don't want any innocent blood spilt.

258
00:24:28,384 --> 00:24:31,803
Bide your time.
There's a time and a place.

259
00:24:31,887 --> 00:24:34,764
Do as I say now. Now!

260
00:24:39,353 --> 00:24:42,021
- Open that gate.
- Sean. Mossie.

261
00:24:47,361 --> 00:24:49,445
Put your guns away.

262
00:24:49,530 --> 00:24:51,823
- Guns away?
- Yes.

263
00:24:51,907 --> 00:24:54,325
- Bring the cows in.
- Bring them through.

264
00:24:54,410 --> 00:24:57,287
Stand aside. Stand aside.
Go on, stand over.

265
00:24:58,873 --> 00:25:00,248
Stand aside.

266
00:25:00,332 --> 00:25:03,209
Dessie. Dessie, usher them in.

267
00:25:03,294 --> 00:25:05,753
Stand by them, stand by them.

268
00:25:09,925 --> 00:25:13,052
Let them through.

269
00:25:20,895 --> 00:25:25,064
Siuil, siuil, siuil a ruin

270
00:25:26,483 --> 00:25:32,197
Siuil go socair agus siuil go ciuin

271
00:25:32,281 --> 00:25:37,994
Siuil go doras agus ealaigh lium

272
00:25:38,078 --> 00:25:46,085
Is go dte tu mo mhuirnin slan

273
00:25:47,046 --> 00:25:51,883
I wish, I wish, I wish in vain

274
00:25:51,967 --> 00:25:56,930
I wish I had my heart again

275
00:25:57,014 --> 00:26:03,353
And vainly think I'd not complain

276
00:26:03,437 --> 00:26:11,277
Is go dte tu mo mhuirnin slan

277
00:26:12,112 --> 00:26:17,367
Siuil, siuil, siuil a ruin

278
00:26:17,451 --> 00:26:22,163
Siuil go socair agus siuil go ciuin

279
00:26:22,248 --> 00:26:23,498
Siuil go...

280
00:26:23,582 --> 00:26:25,959
I want Gralton!

281
00:26:26,043 --> 00:26:28,670
- He's under arrest!
- What for?

282
00:26:28,796 --> 00:26:32,382
There'll be no more anarchy in Leitrim.
No more of your kangaroo courts.

283
00:26:32,466 --> 00:26:34,092
Show us the warrant!

284
00:26:36,553 --> 00:26:38,471
You've got to get out! Get out!

285
00:26:40,599 --> 00:26:42,267
Go! Go!

286
00:26:49,900 --> 00:26:53,236
Get out! Get out!

287
00:26:53,320 --> 00:26:56,030
Get out of here!

288
00:26:56,115 --> 00:26:58,324
Get away with you!

289
00:27:20,931 --> 00:27:23,975
- What are you gonna do?
- I'll head to the States.

290
00:27:27,896 --> 00:27:31,274
Oh, that looks a sore one. I'm sorry.

291
00:27:31,358 --> 00:27:32,775
It's nothing.

292
00:27:32,901 --> 00:27:36,446
It was worth it to see the expression
on his face, the bastard.

293
00:27:37,156 --> 00:27:40,783
Will you say goodbye to Mam for me?
They're watching the farm.

294
00:27:42,494 --> 00:27:44,454
How long are you gone for, Jimmy?

295
00:27:45,247 --> 00:27:46,998
Till things calm down.

296
00:27:47,082 --> 00:27:50,168
There's a few pistol boys
keen to make a name for themselves.

297
00:27:51,128 --> 00:27:54,589
I've a few good comrades over
in New York who'll help me find work.

298
00:27:57,301 --> 00:27:59,218
Mossie's waiting for me.

299
00:28:01,138 --> 00:28:03,264
What if I asked you
to come with me, Oonagh?

300
00:28:06,101 --> 00:28:08,644
What if my mother wasn't fading?

301
00:28:08,729 --> 00:28:11,481
What if I wasn't the only daughter?
What if my dad wouldn't fall apart?

302
00:28:12,608 --> 00:28:14,692
What if I wasn't so trapped, Jimmy?

303
00:28:15,694 --> 00:28:17,278
What if, Oonagh?

304
00:28:19,448 --> 00:28:21,532
And follow you around?

305
00:28:21,617 --> 00:28:24,369
From one battle to the next?
Can I take that?

306
00:28:28,916 --> 00:28:30,958
Are these the only clothes you have?

307
00:28:32,169 --> 00:28:34,796
I hear they sell clothes in New York.

308
00:28:34,922 --> 00:28:36,798
I suppose so.

309
00:28:38,759 --> 00:28:40,676
Jimmy...

310
00:28:45,099 --> 00:28:49,602
You'll be in my heart, girl.
No matter what.

311
00:28:49,686 --> 00:28:51,354
Till the day I die.

312
00:29:26,682 --> 00:29:31,310
Well, Jimmy...
I think you lost your bet.

313
00:29:31,395 --> 00:29:33,855
Couldn't stay away.
Like a moth to a flame.

314
00:29:33,981 --> 00:29:35,606
More like a dog to a post.

315
00:29:35,691 --> 00:29:38,234
That feckin' gable's
never been right anyway.

316
00:29:38,318 --> 00:29:40,570
- I wonder who built that, Tommy.
- Dessie did.

317
00:29:42,489 --> 00:29:44,323
Are you ready for this again, Jimmy?

318
00:29:47,828 --> 00:29:50,621
Jeez. Life's too short.

319
00:29:50,706 --> 00:29:53,207
- We've no choice, do we?
- No.

320
00:29:53,292 --> 00:29:55,751
- Come on, there's work to be done.
- Aye.

321
00:30:04,219 --> 00:30:05,845
It's a beaut, eh?

322
00:30:19,401 --> 00:30:22,528
Is that what you had in that trunk
that near broke my back, is it?

323
00:30:22,613 --> 00:30:24,822
It'll be well worth it, Mossie.

324
00:30:26,033 --> 00:30:28,618
- What the hell is it, Jimmy?
- His pet.

325
00:30:33,707 --> 00:30:37,043
Looks grand, but I don't know
what we're gonna feed it on.

326
00:30:50,224 --> 00:30:52,433
We'll have music
while we work now.

327
00:30:55,437 --> 00:30:57,855
It's a beautiful sound, isn't it?

328
00:31:00,817 --> 00:31:02,860
Nice, Jimmy.

329
00:31:02,945 --> 00:31:06,155
Jimmy, did you ever go to
a jazz club when you were in Harlem?

330
00:31:06,240 --> 00:31:10,493
I did, aye. The Savoy Ballroom.
Aye, grand musicians.

331
00:31:10,577 --> 00:31:12,453
The only place in the United States

332
00:31:12,538 --> 00:31:14,830
where black and white
dance together in peace.

333
00:31:14,915 --> 00:31:16,415
- Really?
- Aye, marvellous.

334
00:31:16,500 --> 00:31:18,626
Did you ever dance
with a black woman, Jimmy?

335
00:31:20,337 --> 00:31:23,214
You know what the most
amazing thing about it was?

336
00:31:23,298 --> 00:31:26,175
They've two legs like everyone else.

337
00:31:26,260 --> 00:31:30,096
- Go on there, Jimmy. Show us a few steps.
- Go on!

338
00:31:30,180 --> 00:31:31,514
Honestly...

339
00:31:31,598 --> 00:31:34,433
- Please, go on.
- Please, Jimmy, come on.

340
00:31:34,518 --> 00:31:37,103
All right, all right, all right!

341
00:31:37,187 --> 00:31:38,938
All right.

342
00:31:40,732 --> 00:31:43,776
- If I can only remember them.
- Ah, go on, Jimmy, son.

343
00:31:46,196 --> 00:31:48,030
Go on, Jimmy.

344
00:31:56,999 --> 00:32:00,334
I've a chicken at home
that can do exactly the same dance.

345
00:32:17,227 --> 00:32:18,686
Come on.

346
00:32:24,276 --> 00:32:27,069
Stop leading, Oonagh.

347
00:32:42,252 --> 00:32:45,755
Now, come on. Shim-sham time!

348
00:32:46,715 --> 00:32:48,174
And shim-sham.

349
00:32:50,761 --> 00:32:52,386
Right foot first.

350
00:32:53,805 --> 00:32:56,223
And right again.
All right! Same again.

351
00:32:58,060 --> 00:33:01,187
Left foot again. Good.

352
00:33:01,271 --> 00:33:06,025
Oh, show us the beginning.
Show us the beginning. That's very hard.

353
00:33:06,109 --> 00:33:09,904
Let's go back to the start.
Right foot first.

354
00:33:09,988 --> 00:33:11,238
And right.

355
00:33:12,407 --> 00:33:13,783
And a right again.

356
00:33:15,035 --> 00:33:17,286
Left foot now. All right.

357
00:33:18,205 --> 00:33:19,288
Right again.

358
00:33:27,464 --> 00:33:30,549
Good work!

359
00:33:38,725 --> 00:33:41,018
"I went out to the Hazel Wood,

360
00:33:41,103 --> 00:33:43,396
"Because a fire was in my head.

361
00:33:44,147 --> 00:33:46,524
"And cut and peeled a hazel wand,

362
00:33:46,608 --> 00:33:48,567
"And hooked a berry to a thread.

363
00:33:50,028 --> 00:33:52,947
"And when white moths
were on the wing,

364
00:33:53,031 --> 00:33:55,700
"And moth-like stars
were flickering out,

365
00:33:56,576 --> 00:34:00,579
"I dropped the berry in a stream
And caught a little silver trout.

366
00:34:02,332 --> 00:34:07,378
"When I had laid it on the floor,
I went to blow the fire a-flame.

367
00:34:07,462 --> 00:34:11,507
"But something rustled on the floor
And someone called me by my name.

368
00:34:12,175 --> 00:34:15,594
"It had become a glimmering girl,

369
00:34:15,679 --> 00:34:20,391
"With apple blossom in her hair
Who called me by my name and ran,

370
00:34:20,475 --> 00:34:23,144
"And faded through the brightening air.

371
00:34:24,146 --> 00:34:26,480
"Though I am old with wandering,

372
00:34:26,565 --> 00:34:28,941
"Through hollow lands and hilly lands,

373
00:34:29,401 --> 00:34:31,652
"I will find out where she has gone

374
00:34:32,154 --> 00:34:34,739
"And kiss her lips and take her hands,

375
00:34:34,823 --> 00:34:37,283
"And walk among long dappled grass,

376
00:34:37,868 --> 00:34:40,745
"And pluck till time and times are done,

377
00:34:41,621 --> 00:34:46,542
"The silver apples of the moon,
The golden apples of the sun."

378
00:34:46,626 --> 00:34:48,502
- Beautiful, Roisin.
- That was beautiful.

379
00:34:48,587 --> 00:34:50,629
- It was beautiful, darling.
- Thank you.

380
00:34:50,714 --> 00:34:52,548
You made it sound so real.

381
00:34:53,049 --> 00:34:56,260
Next week, we'll talk about
what influenced Yeats.

382
00:34:56,344 --> 00:34:58,637
Irish folklore, Greek myth,

383
00:34:58,722 --> 00:35:04,018
and even Maud Gonne's
continuous refusal of him. Erm...

384
00:35:04,102 --> 00:35:08,689
But for now, let's just talk about how
it felt as the words swept over you.

385
00:35:08,774 --> 00:35:11,692
Ah, but sure, you know,
does all that longing,

386
00:35:11,777 --> 00:35:15,154
does it break your heart
or does it fill you up with hope?

387
00:35:15,238 --> 00:35:18,532
You know, the way she's always,
er, just out of reach,

388
00:35:18,617 --> 00:35:21,452
or changing shape or whatever, you know.

389
00:35:21,536 --> 00:35:23,913
But I suppose, er, in fairness to him,

390
00:35:23,997 --> 00:35:26,123
he tried till his dying breath
to find her.

391
00:35:41,723 --> 00:35:43,557
Here we are, how are you getting on?

392
00:35:43,642 --> 00:35:46,644
I was just
trying to get the overall shape here...

393
00:35:46,728 --> 00:35:50,147
Loosen everything up and just
see what happens, but great work.

394
00:35:50,232 --> 00:35:51,565
That's lovely.

395
00:35:54,486 --> 00:35:57,154
- How are you getting on, Ruari?
- Good, yeah.

396
00:35:57,239 --> 00:35:58,280
Great, I'd say...

397
00:35:58,365 --> 00:36:00,825
One, two. Cross. Cross, go on.

398
00:36:00,909 --> 00:36:03,410
Keep that head
beneath the chin. Good man.

399
00:36:03,495 --> 00:36:05,412
Keep that guard up.

400
00:36:05,497 --> 00:36:08,874
Jab. Cross now, cross.
And guard up.

401
00:36:08,959 --> 00:36:12,044
Alright, Shane, Shane,
take a wee break there now.

402
00:36:12,128 --> 00:36:14,755
- Good man.
- Go on then, tiger.

403
00:36:14,881 --> 00:36:16,924
One, two. One, two.

404
00:36:17,008 --> 00:36:20,135
Don't forget your guard. Good man.

405
00:36:20,220 --> 00:36:23,305
- That was below the belt, was it?
- Come on, jab.

406
00:36:23,390 --> 00:36:26,225
- Come on, wake up. One, two.
- Good man.

407
00:36:26,309 --> 00:36:29,186
That's the one that's gonna
give him a pain in the belly.

408
00:36:29,271 --> 00:36:31,856
Hold on. Hold on, hold on.
You're all over the place here now.

409
00:36:31,940 --> 00:36:34,817
Come on. Straight shots, right?

410
00:36:34,901 --> 00:36:36,944
Stand back a little bit.
Go on, now.

411
00:36:37,028 --> 00:36:39,071
- Go on, good man.
- Is that the best you got?

412
00:36:39,155 --> 00:36:42,575
- Straight, straight.
- Come on! I can't feel it.

413
00:36:42,659 --> 00:36:45,494
- Ow! Jesus!
- Well, that's what you get...

414
00:36:45,579 --> 00:36:47,705
Feckin' gobshite!

415
00:36:49,249 --> 00:36:52,376
"The Pearse-Connolly
Hall opens again."

416
00:36:52,460 --> 00:36:55,212
I see they've a dance
this weekend.

417
00:36:55,297 --> 00:36:56,922
Maybe we should pop along, huh?

418
00:36:57,007 --> 00:37:00,509
Hmm. Advertised in
a communist newspaper. Look at that.

419
00:37:00,594 --> 00:37:04,388
"Classes of every sort."
Defiance, that's what that is.

420
00:37:06,141 --> 00:37:09,435
Well, with respect,
it's probably best to just ignore it.

421
00:37:09,519 --> 00:37:12,771
Repression breeds belligerence,
isn't that what they say?

422
00:37:15,400 --> 00:37:19,445
Yeah, "From each according to his ability,
to each according to his need."

423
00:37:19,529 --> 00:37:22,156
The Communist Manifesto.

424
00:37:22,240 --> 00:37:26,076
Quasi religious. It's like
"Love thy neighbour as thyself."

425
00:37:26,161 --> 00:37:27,453
The language of brotherhood.

426
00:37:27,537 --> 00:37:30,539
It spreads like wildfire
in a world of rampant greed.

427
00:37:30,624 --> 00:37:33,876
Do you realise how attractive that is
in the slums?

428
00:37:33,960 --> 00:37:37,755
To the poor, to the unemployed?
The landless?

429
00:37:37,839 --> 00:37:40,633
This Depression has destroyed lives
around the world.

430
00:37:40,717 --> 00:37:42,217
Misery breeds desperation,

431
00:37:42,302 --> 00:37:45,220
and it only takes a handful of
communists to set the fuse...

432
00:37:45,305 --> 00:37:46,639
Don't get carried away now.

433
00:37:46,723 --> 00:37:49,683
There can only be 150 or 200 communists
in the entire country.

434
00:37:49,768 --> 00:37:52,645
One man, one book,
changed the world. Karl Marx.

435
00:37:52,729 --> 00:37:55,439
Jimmy Gralton isn't Karl Marx.
He's just a worker, now.

436
00:37:55,523 --> 00:38:00,486
Listen, his mother ran a mobile library.
Never patronise the self-taught man,

437
00:38:00,570 --> 00:38:03,072
especially someone
who worked down the mines.

438
00:38:03,156 --> 00:38:06,492
He's a maverick, all right,
but he's a lightweight maverick, so...

439
00:38:06,576 --> 00:38:09,411
Fire in his soul
and a plan in his head.

440
00:38:09,496 --> 00:38:12,873
You can't buy him off. No.

441
00:38:12,999 --> 00:38:15,668
He's not greedy, he's not selfish.

442
00:38:16,336 --> 00:38:20,673
You know...
They remind me of the first martyrs.

443
00:38:21,549 --> 00:38:25,344
D'you ever read about those union
organisers in the States? The Wobblies.

444
00:38:25,428 --> 00:38:27,721
Entering towns and factories.

445
00:38:28,515 --> 00:38:32,101
Thrown into prisons, lynched, murdered.

446
00:38:32,185 --> 00:38:34,061
If every priest had their grit...

447
00:38:34,145 --> 00:38:37,064
Well, there's nothing
as dramatic as that here.

448
00:38:37,148 --> 00:38:40,484
It's just a tiny little hall,
in a country bog.

449
00:38:40,568 --> 00:38:43,612
- Yeah, with a gramophone.
- With a gramophone.

450
00:38:43,697 --> 00:38:45,572
First it's the dancing, then the books.

451
00:38:45,657 --> 00:38:47,282
He'll start at the bottom
with their feet

452
00:38:47,367 --> 00:38:50,202
and work up to their brains,
if they have any.

453
00:38:50,787 --> 00:38:53,622
That bloody book. Das Kapital.

454
00:38:55,792 --> 00:38:57,626
I'm going to get one, too.

455
00:38:57,711 --> 00:38:59,378
Going to get the book, are you?

456
00:38:59,462 --> 00:39:02,089
A feckin' gramophone,
you bloody eejit.

457
00:39:02,966 --> 00:39:05,759
Is there any marmalade in this house?

458
00:39:05,844 --> 00:39:08,512
There is. Especially for you.

459
00:39:08,596 --> 00:39:10,556
- Thank you.
- Go easy, go easy.

460
00:39:18,940 --> 00:39:20,566
See you in a little while.

461
00:39:27,365 --> 00:39:28,657
Jimmy!

462
00:39:45,467 --> 00:39:46,800
- Hi!
- Hello.

463
00:39:46,885 --> 00:39:48,594
This is Colm and Clodagh.

464
00:39:48,678 --> 00:39:51,055
Colm, young man. Lovely to meet you.

465
00:39:51,139 --> 00:39:53,891
This is Jimmy who brought you
the presents from America.

466
00:39:53,975 --> 00:39:55,476
Lovely to meet you.

467
00:39:55,560 --> 00:39:59,188
Jimmy. Time flies.
Some things haven't changed.

468
00:39:59,272 --> 00:40:02,524
- You're looking well, Fintan.
- Thanks, Jimmy.

469
00:40:02,609 --> 00:40:04,485
Now, will you two, will you dance?

470
00:40:04,569 --> 00:40:06,695
A little. Maybe a little.

471
00:40:06,780 --> 00:40:09,782
- Just a little bit?
- And thanks for the presents.

472
00:40:09,866 --> 00:40:11,825
- Oh, did you like it?
- Yep.

473
00:40:11,910 --> 00:40:15,579
Lovely. And you played with them?
That's the main thing.

474
00:40:15,663 --> 00:40:18,207
- We know these two men.
- Who are these two?

475
00:40:18,291 --> 00:40:21,126
Yeah,
that's Michael Fitzpatrick there.

476
00:40:22,170 --> 00:40:23,545
Er, Fiona Gallagher.

477
00:40:23,630 --> 00:40:25,339
- There's Fiona.
- Yes, I know you.

478
00:40:25,423 --> 00:40:28,383
- Amy Gilligan.
- Amy Gilligan, right. Just a moment.

479
00:40:33,431 --> 00:40:36,350
- Where have you come from?
- Up the road, Father.

480
00:40:36,434 --> 00:40:38,852
- Up the road where?
- Up the road and round the bend.

481
00:40:38,937 --> 00:40:42,648
- What bend would that be, young man?
- It's a fierce bendy road, Father.

482
00:40:42,732 --> 00:40:46,110
- What bend was it, lads?
- Up at O'Hara's white horse.

483
00:40:46,194 --> 00:40:49,029
Marie O'Keefe, what are you doing here?

484
00:40:49,447 --> 00:40:51,115
I came here to dance, Father.

485
00:40:51,199 --> 00:40:54,201
Is the proper parish dance
not good enough for you, huh?

486
00:40:54,285 --> 00:40:55,702
Yes, Father.

487
00:40:55,787 --> 00:40:58,664
Does your father know
you're in a car with outsiders? Huh?

488
00:40:59,833 --> 00:41:03,293
Put her name down. Marie O'Keefe,
And what's that driver's name?

489
00:41:05,046 --> 00:41:07,005
Think we're doing more harm than good.

490
00:41:07,090 --> 00:41:10,592
- Look at the wee child.
- This poor child, will you look at her?

491
00:41:10,677 --> 00:41:15,180
That child should be home in bed.
You ought to be ashamed of yourselves.

492
00:41:15,515 --> 00:41:17,057
And who is this behind them?

493
00:41:17,142 --> 00:41:20,519
- Who's that, the fella smoking?
- That's Brian McMahon.

494
00:41:20,603 --> 00:41:22,437
And Tommy Doyle.

495
00:44:53,775 --> 00:44:57,277
What is this craze for pleasure?

496
00:44:58,821 --> 00:45:03,200
This fascination with the materialist?

497
00:45:03,284 --> 00:45:05,535
The pagan, the Anglo Saxon?

498
00:45:05,620 --> 00:45:11,458
And most recently,
the Los Angelisation of our culture?

499
00:45:12,043 --> 00:45:15,504
What is wrong
with being true to ourselves,

500
00:45:15,588 --> 00:45:17,756
to our deepest roots,

501
00:45:17,840 --> 00:45:21,426
to our own true Irish values?

502
00:45:23,096 --> 00:45:27,933
Did not Cromwell himself
try to burn all the harps in the land,

503
00:45:28,017 --> 00:45:32,896
murder our priests, exile our musicians?

504
00:45:33,981 --> 00:45:38,068
They tried to crush our language,
our song, our dance,

505
00:45:38,152 --> 00:45:43,323
but our forefathers resisted them
in their hedge schools,

506
00:45:43,408 --> 00:45:45,742
risking their very lives.

507
00:45:46,786 --> 00:45:50,080
Oh, how they must turn in their graves

508
00:45:50,164 --> 00:45:56,962
to see our youths debase themselves
in Jimmy Gralton's hall.

509
00:46:40,756 --> 00:46:42,799
Jazz music.

510
00:46:43,843 --> 00:46:49,723
Rhythms from darkest Africa
that inflame the passions.

511
00:46:50,850 --> 00:46:53,768
Pelvic thrusts
and salacious body grappling,

512
00:46:53,853 --> 00:46:58,398
instead of the elegance and beauty
of our own Irish dances.

513
00:47:00,443 --> 00:47:04,196
And then, of course, we have company
keeping under the stars at night.

514
00:47:05,656 --> 00:47:07,782
Joy-riding until dawn...

515
00:47:08,993 --> 00:47:14,748
with unsuitables on the prowl
from distant parts in their motor cars.

516
00:47:14,832 --> 00:47:18,960
Occasions of sin
multiplied beyond our imagination.

517
00:47:21,047 --> 00:47:25,675
But there is something even more evil
hatching in that hall.

518
00:47:26,719 --> 00:47:31,806
Gralton and his crew... are communists.

519
00:47:33,267 --> 00:47:34,768
They are atheists.

520
00:47:34,852 --> 00:47:40,190
They deny the existence of God,
the Trinity

521
00:47:40,274 --> 00:47:42,067
and the Virgin birth.

522
00:47:44,445 --> 00:47:47,447
So, our community faces a choice.

523
00:47:48,449 --> 00:47:52,827
Is it Christ... or is it Gralton?

524
00:48:04,340 --> 00:48:08,260
Now, the Church
has a right, and even a duty,

525
00:48:08,344 --> 00:48:09,970
to protect the vulnerable.

526
00:48:10,054 --> 00:48:15,016
So what I do now,
I do in the spirit of God's love.

527
00:48:16,394 --> 00:48:19,312
I will now read out
the names of those people

528
00:48:19,397 --> 00:48:23,733
who attended Gralton's Hall last night.

